headline: The Ice Cream That Beat Costco’s Hot Dog as the Best Money Loser in Business
summary: Business students learn about the concept of a loss leader: a product a store sells at a loss, to bait shoppers into buying something profitable.  For decades, there was no better example than  Costco’s  $1.50 hot dog-and-soda combo, a deal so legendary that it sells 130 million a year.  It is a towering, soft-serve ice cream cone that typically costs 40 cents—and customers buy about 700 million a year.
